# Architecture (per-project decisions)

> TODO: fill in BEFORE starting the project. Delete sections that don't apply.

## Pattern of choice
<!-- choose ONE -->
- [ ] **MV (Model-View)** — `@Observable` model used directly in views. No ViewModel layer.
- [ ] **IVO (Input-View-Output)** — `@Observable` ViewModel with `enum Input` + `trigger(_:)`.

## Folder layout
```
Sources/
  App/                  # App entry + DI composition root
  Features/
    <FeatureName>/
      Views/            # SwiftUI views
      ViewModels/       # @Observable view models (if IVO/MVVM)
      Models/           # Domain models / SwiftData @Model entities
  Services/             # actors: network, persistence, analytics
  DesignSystem/         # Colors, Typography, reusable Views
  Resources/            # Assets, Localizable.xcstrings
```

## Dependency injection
- Use **constructor injection** for services. No singletons unless justified.
- Pass dependencies down through view initializers or `@Environment`.

## Naming
- Views: `<Feature>View`, subviews: `<Feature><Part>View`.
- ViewModels: `<Feature>ViewModel`.
- Services: `<Domain>Service` (typically an `actor`).
- Errors: nested `enum Error: LocalizedError` inside the owning type.

## Protocols — only when there is a real need
Do NOT introduce a `<Domain>ServiceProtocol` by default. Add a protocol only when there is a concrete reason:
- a mock implementation is needed for unit tests,
- a preview-only fake is needed for SwiftUI previews,
- there are (or will soon be) multiple real implementations,
- the service is exposed across module boundaries that require abstraction.

Otherwise — keep the concrete type. Less code, easier to read, easier to refactor later.
